'''Aaron Buchanan Hickey''' (born 10 June 2002) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defender (association football)#Full-back|full-back]] for {{English football updater|Brentfor}} club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

Hickey played youth football for [[Heart of Midlothian F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Heart of Midlothian]] and [[Celtic F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Celtic]], before returning to Hearts where he made his senior debut in 2019. After two seasons in Italy with [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]], he signed for English club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in 2022.

Hickey represented Scotland at under-17 youth level, before making his senior international debut in 2022.

== Early life ==
Hickey attended [[St Ninian's High School, Kirkintilloch|St Ninian's High School]] in [[Kirkintilloch]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aaron-hickey-reveals-lessons-karamoko-16202268|title=Aaron Hickey details his Karamoko Dembele lessons as Hearts kid upstages school pal|last=Ralston|first=Gary|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|date=26 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526095144/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aaron-hickey-reveals-lessons-karamoko-16202268|archive-date=26 May 2019}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
After spending time in the youth system at [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]], Hickey had a spell with the [[Celtic F.C. Under-20s and Academy|academy teams]] at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]. After four years at Celtic he chose to return to Hearts in 2018, with Celtic receiving 30% of a future transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/17977923.manchester-city-plot-swoop-hearts-aaron-hickey/|title=Manchester City plot Aaron Hickey swoop|website=Evening Times |date=18 October 2019 }}</ref><ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53999267|title=The Scot who turned down Bayern|work=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2020 }}</ref>

===Hearts===
On 10 May 2019, Hickey made his debut for the club in a 2–1 loss away to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], in the penultimate game of the 2018–19 season.<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heartsfc.co.uk/squads/first-team/playing-squad/aaron-hickey|title=Aaron Hickey|website=Heart of Midlothian F.C.|access-date=25 May 2019|archive-date=21 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200921055138/https://www.heartsfc.co.uk/squads/first-team/playing-squad/aaron-hickey|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ghosh |first=Ratul |date=9 April 2022 |title=Aaron Hickey: The most experienced teenager in Europe will join Brentford in a £14m transfer |work=Foot The Ball |url=https://www.foottheball.com/rising-ballers/aaron-hickey-player-profile-career-teenager-stats-potential-bologna-scotland-future/}}</ref> On 25 May 2019, Hickey started in the [[2019 Scottish Cup Final]] against Celtic, becoming the youngest player to appear in the final since [[John Fleck (footballer)|John Fleck]] in [[2008 Scottish Cup Final|2008]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/latest-hearts-news/hearts-team-news-16-year-old-aaron-hickey-starts-but-uche-ikpeazu-on-bench-1-4934613|title=Hearts team news: 16-year-old Aaron Hickey starts but Uche Ikpeazu on bench|website=Edinburgh Evening News|date=25 May 2019|access-date=25 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525141751/https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/latest-hearts-news/hearts-team-news-16-year-old-aaron-hickey-starts-but-uche-ikpeazu-on-bench-1-4934613|archive-date=25 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 22 September 2019, he scored his first senior goal, the winner in the [[Edinburgh derby]] as Hearts won 2–1 away at [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49705125|title=Hibs 1–2 Hearts: Aaron Hickey nets late Edinburgh derby winner|work=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2019}}</ref>

In August 2020 he was linked with a transfer away from the club, with interest from German club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53728356|title=Aaron Hickey: Hearts defender very impressed by Bayern Munich visit|work=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/sport-opinion/hearts-aaron-hickey-cannot-turn-down-chance-become-next-alphonso-davies-2946232|title=Hearts' Aaron Hickey cannot turn down chance to become the next Alphonso Davies|website=www.scotsman.com |date=18 August 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/18630744.bayern-munich-closing-deals-celtic-youngster-aaron-hickey/|title=Bayern Munich closing in on deals for Celtic youngster and Aaron Hickey|website=HeraldScotland |date=5 August 2020 }}</ref> Italian club [[Bologna FC|Bologna]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/aaron-hickey-bologna-latest-long-line-clubs-be-linked-hearts-starlet-2930690|title=Aaron Hickey: Bologna latest in long line of clubs to be linked with Hearts starlet|website=www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com |date=2 August 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/sport/football/hearts-defender-aaron-hickey-make-18780850|title=Bologna expecting Aaron Hickey decision today as Italian side await answer|first=Robert|last=Fairnie|date=17 August 2020|website=edinburghlive}}</ref> English club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53629596|title=Aaron Hickey: Bayern Munich, Bologna & Aston Villa chasing Hearts teenager|work=BBC Sport |date=2 August 2020}}</ref> and French club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/aaron-hickey-transfer-latest-lyon-22528666|title=Aaron Hickey transfer latest as Lyon join race for Hearts youngster9i|first=Scott|last=McDermott|date=15 August 2020|website=Daily Record}}</ref> Hearts manager [[Craig Levein]] also revealed that Celtic had made "five or six" attempts to sign Hickey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53657990|title=Celtic tried to sign Hickey – Levein|work=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2020 }}</ref> Towards the end of the month the BBC reported that Bologna had made the first official bid for Hickey,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53937777|title=Aaron Hickey: Bologna steal march on Bayern Munich after making Hearts offer|work=BBC Sport |date=27 August 2020}}</ref> although Hearts said that the offer was too low.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53953896|title=Bologna's Aaron Hickey bid 'nowhere near' Hearts' valuation|work=BBC Sport |date=28 August 2020}}</ref>

===Bologna===
Bologna made an updated offer for Hickey, which was accepted by Hearts on 8 September 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54078774|title=Hearts accept Bologna's Hickey bid|work=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2020 }}</ref> On 24 September 2020, Hickey completed a moved to the [[Serie A]] side for an undisclosed fee believed to be around £1.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53979108 |title=Aaron Hickey: Bologna sign teenager from Hearts |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=24 September 2020 |access-date=24 September 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/hickey-to-bologna/|title=Hickey to Bologna|date=24 September 2020|website=BolognaFC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54092790|title=Facing Zlatan would be crazy – Hickey|work=BBC Sport |date=9 September 2020 }}</ref> He said he chose Bologna over Bayern due to the Italian club's family feel, and their intention to use him in their first-team.<ref name="auto"/> Due to the suspension of regular left-back [[Mitchell Dijks]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/ex-hearts-star-aaron-hickey-line-bologna-debut-tonight-against-parma-and-how-fans-can-watch-him-action-2985401 |title=Ex-Hearts star Aaron Hickey in line for Bologna debut tonight against Parma – and how fans can watch him in action |first=Joel |last=Sked |newspaper=Edinburgh Evening News |date=28 September 2020 |access-date=29 September 2020}}</ref> Hickey made his first Serie A appearance on 28 September in a 4–1 win against [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54338698 |title=Aaron Hickey: Sinisa Mihajlovic says Scot has 'great future' after Bologna debut |website=BBC Sport |date=29 September 2020 |access-date=29 September 2020}}</ref> That meant Hickey followed [[Denis Law]], [[Joe Jordan]], [[Graeme Souness]] and [[Liam Henderson]] to be the fifth Scotsman to play in the [[Italian Football Championship]] since its re-[[brand]] in [[1929–30 Serie A|1929]] to [[Serie A]].<ref name=fifthscot>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/uk-sport/18756014.sinisa-mihajlovic-talks-aaron-hickey-scot-makes-successful-bologna-bow/|title=Sinisa Mihajlovic talks up Aaron Hickey after Scot makes successful Bologna bow|date=29 September 2020|website=The Herald}}</ref> Hickey's first season at Bologna was cut short by shoulder surgery in March 2021, restricting him to 12 appearances, even though he clocked up the fourth-highest minutes total of any under-21 player across the top five European leagues.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Harris |first=Jay |date=9 July 2022 |title=Aaron Hickey to Brentford: What will Thomas Frank's side be getting for their money? |work=The Athletic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3403183/2022/07/09/aaron-hickey-brentford-position/}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was nominated for the [[Golden Boy (award)|2021 Golden Boy award]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDougall |first1=Mark |title=Hickey earns Golden Boy nomination as ex-Hearts star listed on incredible list |url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/sport/football/aaron-hickey-earns-golden-boy-20824981 |access-date=18 June 2021 |work=Edinburgh Live |date=15 June 2021}}</ref>

Hickey returned to Bologna's first team following his injury, starting the first game of the [[2021–22 Bologna F.C. 1909 season|2021–22]] season against [[U.S. Salernitana 1919|Salernitana]], which Bologna won 3–2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/sport/football/aaron-hickey-makes-winning-bologna-21376406|title=Aaron Hickey makes winning Bologna return as ex Hearts man starts in chaotic Serie A opener|work=edinburghlive.co.uk|first=Robbie|last=Copeland|date=23 August 2021|access-date=13 September 2021}}</ref>
On 21 September 2021, Hickey scored his first goal for [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]], in their 2–2 draw with [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] in the Serie A.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aaron-hickey-scores-first-bologna-25039629|title=Aaron Hickey scores first Bologna goal as Scotland rising star earns his moment of redemption after Inter nightmare|work=dailyrecord.co.uk|first=Charlotte|last=Cohen|date=21 September 2021|access-date=21 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58656800|title=Hickey proud to match Scottish legends|work=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2021 }}</ref> That made him the fourth Scot to score in Serie A, as Henderson did not score for Empoli that season until January.<ref name=fitalia>{{Cite web|url=https://football-italia.net/video-hickey-fourth-scot-to-score-in-serie-a/|title=Video: Hickey fourth Scot to score in Serie A – Football Italia|first=Mm|last=Says|date=21 September 2021|website=football-italia.net}}</ref> In November 2021 he was described as "flourishing in Serie A with Bologna".<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/nov/27/aaron-hickey-scotland-bologna-serie-a-interview|title=Aaron Hickey: 'You go to bed thinking about playing at San Siro – that's a wow moment'|date=27 November 2021|website=The Guardian}}</ref> On 24 April 2022, Hickey became the first Scot to score 5 goals in a single Serie A season since [[Graeme Souness]] in [[1984–85 Serie A|1984–85]] for [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballtransfers.com/en/transfer-news/it-serie-a/2021-10-who-is-aaron-hickey-scot-abroad-impressing-serie|title=Who is Aaron Hickey? The €24m Bologna starlet set to join Arsenal|website=Football Transfers|date=16 May 2022|access-date=3 June 2022}}</ref>

===Brentford===
Bologna accepted an offer for Hickey from [[Premier League]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in July 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62023903 |title=Aaron Hickey: Brentford agree transfer fee for Bologna and Scotland left-back |website=BBC Sport |first=Kheredine |last=Idessane |date=2 July 2022 |access-date=3 July 2022}}</ref> On 9 July 2022, Brentford announced that they had signed Hickey on a four-year contract, subject to international clearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62105581 |title=Aaron Hickey: Brentford sign Scottish defender from Bologna |website=BBC Sport |date=9 July 2022 |access-date=9 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Aaron Hickey signs for Brentford |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2022/july/aaron-hickey-signs-for-brentford/ |access-date=9 July 2022 |website=www.brentfordfc.com |language=en-gb}}</ref> Hickey regularly played on the right side of defence for Brentford during the 2022–23 season, although he missed a few months due to suffering an ankle ligament injury in October.<ref name = athleticfeb23/> In 2023, when [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] were linked with a transfer, [[Thomas Frank (football manager)|Thomas Frank]] said, "We will not sell him. He's not even been here a year, with all due respect. I think he's a very good young player that I think has a fantastic future ahead of him. There needs to be a little bit more to get into the City team in terms of performances. I think he's done well and I really like him. I think he can get up there."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richardson |first=John |date=23 September 2023 |title=Man Utd, Liverpool and Arsenal in three-way battle for Brentford star Aaron Hickey |work=Daily Mirror |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/manutd-liverpool-arsenal-aaron-hickey-31010541}}</ref>

Hickey suffered a serious hamstring injury against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in October 2023; ten months after the injury, it was revealed that due to a setback in his recovery, he would miss most of the 2024–25 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/scotland-defender-aaron-hickey-set-to-miss-majority-of-season-after-fresh-injury-blow|title=Aaron Hickey set to miss majority of season after fresh injury blow|first=Andy|last=Coyle|date=29 August 2024|website=STV News}}</ref> He returned to first-team training in April 2025,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/en/news/article/first-team-aaron-hickey-igor-thiago-injury-update|title=Brentford injury update: Hickey and Thiago return to full training|website=www.brentfordfc.com}}</ref> and made his first appearance in an under-21s game against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] on 5 May, assisting a goal by [[Paris Maghoma]] in a 3–0 victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/aaron-hickey-close-brentford-comeback-094131742.html|title=Aaron Hickey close to Brentford comeback as Thomas Frank delivers timeline|first=Ryan|last=McDonald|date=10 May 2025|website=Yahoo Sports}}</ref> Hickey made his first competitive appearance for 659 days when he was used as a substitute in a 3–1 defeat at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 17 August 2025.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c9wyxqz8qdgo |title=Hickey ends 659 days of hurt as Brentford & Scotland watch on |first=Kheredine |last=Idessane |date=18 August 2025 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=19 August 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
Hickey has represented [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]], making his debut for the side in a goalless draw against [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]] on 5 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=259590&lid=13|title=Aaron Hickey|publisher=Scottish Football Association|access-date=25 May 2019}}</ref> He was selected in the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]] squad for the first time in November 2020,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54717063 |title=Aaron Hickey: Bologna left-back given first Scotland Under-21 call-up |first=Clive |last=Lindsay |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=28 October 2020 |access-date=28 October 2020}}</ref> but withdrew due to injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54889620 |title=Aaron Hickey: Bologna defender one of four to pull out of Scotland U21s squad |first=Andy  |last=Campbell |website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=10 November 2020 |access-date=10 November 2021}}</ref> He was recalled in September 2021,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58654502|title=Hickey back in Scotland U21 squad|website=BBC Sport|access-date=26 June 2025}}</ref> but pulled out from that squad due to another injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/spfl/scottish-premiership/aaron-hickeys-scotland-commitment-defended-21774959 |title=Aaron Hickey's Scotland commitment defended as ex-Hearts star's two year absence continues |first=Ryan |last=McDonald|website=Football Scotland|date=6 October 2021 |access-date=10 November 2021}}</ref> He then also withdrew from the following squad, saying he wanted to rest.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/hickey-withdraws-from-scotland-under-21-squad-needing-rest?top |title=Hickey withdraws from Scotland Under-21 squad needing rest |first=Andy |last=Coyle |website=STV Sport |date=9 November 2021 |access-date=9 November 2021}}</ref>

In March 2022, after being left out of the under-21 squad,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60676556 |title=Aaron Hickey: Bologna full-back left out Scotland Under-21 squad after discussion with Gemmill |first=Nick |last=McPheat |date=9 March 2022 |access-date=26 March 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Hickey was included in the senior Scotland squad for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60745678 |title=Aaron Hickey called up to Scotland squad for Poland friendly |website=BBC Sport |date=15 March 2022 |access-date=15 March 2022}}</ref> He made his senior international debut on 24 March in a 1–1 draw against [[Poland national football team|Poland]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Scotland v Poland: Debutant Aaron Hickey given chance to stake a claim|url=https://www.thetimes.com/uk/scotland/article/scotland-v-poland-debutant-aaron-hickey-given-chance-to-stake-a-claim-d8vcxdf0m|url-access=subscription|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=24 March 2022|access-date=26 June 2025}}</ref>

Due to a hamstring injury suffered in October 2023, Hickey missed UEFA Euro 2024.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/cy7381jw3dro|title=Scotland: Frank stays Hickey still progressing ahead of Euros|date=25 April 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c2lez3l54lwo|title=Scotland: Hickey chances 'not fantastic' as Tierney suffers blow|date=25 April 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c2qvyvx32k0o|title=Scotland defender Aaron Hickey's Euro 2024 chances 'not positive'|date=9 May 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Scotland manager [[Steve Clarke]] said in May 2025 that he was hopeful Hickey could recover in time for Scotland's friendlies against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] and [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]] the following month,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/25175806.premier-league-defender-set-return-time-world-cup-qualifiers/|title=Premier League defender set to make Scotland return in time for World Cup qualifiers|first=Matthew|last=Lindsay|date=20 May 2025|website=The Herald}}</ref> but Hickey was not called up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/25173621.clarke-names-scotland-squad-june-friendly-double-header/|title=Steve Clarke names 25-man Scotland squad for June friendly double-header|first=Josh|last=McCafferty|date=19 May 2025|website=The Herald}}</ref>

After returning to club play in August 2025 following injury, Hickey was recalled by Scotland for the first time in two years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce3j7qv7gvpo|title=Scotland: Hickey back for Denmark & Belarus World Cup qualifiers|date=25 August 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Hickey said his long injury spell had made him stronger mentally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c24z03mzjqvo|title=Aaron Hickey: Brentford full-back 'a lot stronger mentally' on Scotland return|first=Kheredine|last=Idessane|date=30 August 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Hickey primarily played for Hearts as a [[defender (association football)|left-back]], although he can also play as a [[central midfielder]],<ref name="auto"/> and also right-back and centre-back, and his "versatility is yet another key attribute".<ref name="auto1"/> Hickey has been compared to fellow Scottish left-back [[Andy Robertson]], although Hickey has played down the links.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54380207|title=Aaron Hickey: Andy Robertson comparison 'unrealistic', says Bologna debutant|date=4 October 2020|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He mainly played for Bologna as an attacking left wing-back, and scored five goals during the [[2021–22 Serie A]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12607327/aaron-hickey-exclusive-bologna-left-back-open-to-new-challenge-amid-premier-league-and-serie-a-interest |title=Aaron Hickey exclusive: Bologna left-back open to new challenge amid Premier League and Serie A interest |website=Sky Sports |date=23 May 2022 |access-date=2 April 2023}}</ref> Brentford have used him as either a right-back or right wing-back,<ref name = athleticfeb23>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4233839/2023/02/22/mads-roerslev-aaron-hickey-brentford/ |title=Mads Roerslev or Aaron Hickey? Brentford's right-backs offer contrasting qualities |website=The Athletic |date=22 February 2023 |access-date=2 April 2023 |first=Jay |last=Harris}}</ref> Most of his appearances for Scotland have also been as a right-back or right wing-back.

Former Hearts manager [[Craig Levein]] described Hickey by saying that "he's got really good defensive qualities but I don't know if he'll end up being a full-back, he might end up going back into midfield [...] he could be a fantastic holding midfielder with his great awareness of danger and his ability to get out of tight situations with the ball at his feet".<ref name="auto"/> Levein has also said that Hickey is shy, quiet, and reserved.<ref name="auto"/> Hearts captain [[Steven Naismith]] praised Hickey's intelligence, while Hearts head coach [[Robbie Neilson]] praised his maturity, saying that "he's like a 24- or 25-year-old in an 18-year-old's body [...] he's very mature for his age, he's composed, has good physique, ticks all the boxes".<ref name="auto"/>

==Personal life==
On 13 December 2020, he tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/official-club-statement-2/|title=Official statement|date=13 December 2020|website=BolognaFC}}</ref>

Hickey is the cousin of [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] midfielder [[Rocco Hickey-Fugaccia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-sunday-post-dundee/20250330/283811449464034|title=Rocco hoping family ties can inspire cup glory|date=30 March 2025|publisher=Sunday Post}}</ref>

